items.title: Erica lusitanica
items.content_text: On roadside.

items.title: Ulex europaeus
items.content_text: On roadside.

items.title: Paspalum distichum
items.content_text: Growing in the middle of the dried out Riddells Creek at Wybejong Park.

items.title: Lonicera tatarica
items.content_text: Came up in in-laws' garden. It was 1.5m tall when we pulled it out. Could be first record in Australia.

items.title: Ehrharta erecta var. erecta
items.content_text: 2nd pic shows flowers. This is a serious weed. Taking over areas and easily spread by Council graders on dirt roads. Seed are enjoyed by seed-eating birds including finches and crimson rosellas.

items.title: Vellereophyton dealbatum
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Trifolium fragiferum var. fragiferum
items.content_text: Growing alongside a dam.

items.title: Conyza bonariensis
items.content_text: One plant on the side of an old dam. 5cm tall.

items.title: Linum trigynum
items.content_text: Many thousands of plants at this site. Mostly single-stemmed and upright but occasionally multi-stemmed and ascending stems on plants one foot wide. Flowers very small, same size as Cicendia and Sebaea.

items.title: Chrysolina quadrigemina, Hypericum perforatum subsp. veronense
items.content_text: Chrysolina beetles on St John's Wort.

items.title: Cicendia filiformis
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek. Common in the two main open areas at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Tolpis barbata
items.content_text: New species record for Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Linaria pelisseriana
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Hyacinthoides hispanica
items.content_text: Anthers bluer than depicted in photo. Flowers not or sub-secund. Plants growing around the garden, mostly in the lawn.

items.title: Myosotis discolor
items.content_text: A few plants in garden lawn.

items.title: Veronica arvensis
items.content_text: Growing in garden lawn.

items.title: Pieris rapae rapae, Rubus fruticosus spp. agg.
Lotus subbiflorus
items.content_text: Very hairy. Umbel 3-flowered.

items.title: Agonoscelis rutila, Marrubium vulgare
items.content_text: Horehound Bug on Horehound!

items.title: Mentha X piperita, Pieris rapae rapae
items.content_text: Leaves petiolate and 9cm x 3cm further down the stem.

items.title: Dodonaea viscosa 'Purpurea'
items.content_text: Could be Dodonaea viscosa subsp. spatulata but, whichever the case, it is a weed at this location.

items.title: Rubus fruticosus spp. agg., Trapezites phigalioides
Gladiolus cardinalis
items.content_text: A few plants in a (weedy) bush setting. One record on FIS and none at the Herbarium. Got to be a contender for 'prettiest weed'!

items.title: Isolepis levynsiana
items.content_text: In a winter-inundated, summer-dry depression made a little deeper by tyre tracks.

items.title: Isolepis hystrix
items.content_text: Tiny plants in a clay pan - winter inundation, summer dry.

items.title: Sonchus asper s.s., Sonchus asper subsp. glaucescens
Hakea laurina
items.content_text: Just one plant.

items.title: Conyza bonariensis
items.content_text: A new, emerging weed in Riddells Creek. seems to prefer wet sites like drainage lines, road edges and other places prone to temporary inundation.

items.title: Oxalis purpurea
items.content_text: Large infestation in the cemetery.

items.title: Ulex europaeus
items.content_text: Plants at 2 sites.

items.title: Acacia iteaphylla
items.content_text: Only one plant. Obviously a garden escapee. No others have been seen escaping in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Erigeron karvinskianus
items.content_text: Appeared in a damp spot - now removed.

items.title: Conium maculatum
items.content_text: A declared noxious weed.

items.title: Prunella vulgaris
items.content_text: In a swampy area.

items.title: Acacia pravissima
items.content_text: I suspect the main plant was deliberately planted on the side of the track but there were seedlings that were obviously not planted.

items.title: Hypochaeris radicata, Trapezites lutea lutea
items.content_text: First lutea of the season although I haven't had chance to look much before this date.

items.title: Oxalis pes-caprae
items.content_text: This infestation has since been removed but the species appears from time to time around Riddells Creek.

items.title: Freesia alba x Freesia leichtlinii
items.content_text: Location approximate.

items.title: Asparagus asparagoides
items.content_text: Isolated Aparagus asparagoides (Bridal Creeper Clump) on the Kilmore Gisborne Road - Looks like a job for VicRoads.

items.title: Isolepis prolifera
items.content_text: In an inundated part of track.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax, Hypochaeris radicata
items.content_text: Caught by Ellena Best. Feeding on Flatweed (Hypochoeris radicata).
